</div>
			<h1 id="firstHeading" class="firstHeading" lang="en">Borders Abbeys Way</h1>
									<div id="bodyContent" class="mw-body-content">
									<div id="siteSub">From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia</div>
								<div id="contentSub"></div>
												<div id="jump-to-nav" class="mw-jump">
					Jump to:					<a href="#mw-head">navigation</a>, 					<a href="#p-search">search</a>
				</div>
				<div id="mw-content-text" lang="en" dir="ltr" class="mw-content-ltr"><div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:202px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Jedburgh_Abbey1.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a2/Jedburgh_Abbey1.jpg/200px-Jedburgh_Abbey1.jpg" width="200" height="267" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a2/Jedburgh_Abbey1.jpg/300px-Jedburgh_Abbey1.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a2/Jedburgh_Abbey1.jpg/400px-Jedburgh_Abbey1.jpg 2x" data-file-width="768" data-file-height="1024" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Jedburgh_Abbey1.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
Jedburgh Abbey</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:202px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Dryburgh_Abbey1.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/96/Dryburgh_Abbey1.jpg/200px-Dryburgh_Abbey1.jpg" width="200" height="150" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/96/Dryburgh_Abbey1.jpg/300px-Dryburgh_Abbey1.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/96/Dryburgh_Abbey1.jpg/400px-Dryburgh_Abbey1.jpg 2x" data-file-width="1024" data-file-height="768" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Dryburgh_Abbey1.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
Dryburgh Abbey</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>The <b>Borders Abbeys Way</b> is a <a href="/wiki/Long-distance_footpath" title="Long-distance footpath" class="mw-redirect">long-distance footpath</a> in the <a href="/wiki/Scottish_Borders" title="Scottish Borders">Scottish Borders</a> area of <a href="/wiki/Scotland" title="Scotland">Scotland</a>. It is a circular walkway and is 64.5 miles (103&#160;km) long.</p>
<p>The theme of the footpath is the ruined <a href="/wiki/Scottish_Borders" title="Scottish Borders">Borders</a> <a href="/wiki/Abbeys" title="Abbeys" class="mw-redirect">abbeys</a> (established by <a href="/wiki/David_I_of_Scotland" title="David I of Scotland">David I of Scotland</a>) along its way—<a href="/wiki/Kelso_Abbey" title="Kelso Abbey">Kelso Abbey</a>, <a href="/wiki/Jedburgh_Abbey" title="Jedburgh Abbey">Jedburgh Abbey</a>, <a href="/wiki/Melrose_Abbey" title="Melrose Abbey">Melrose Abbey</a> and <a href="/wiki/Dryburgh_Abbey" title="Dryburgh Abbey">Dryburgh Abbey</a>—and it also includes the towns of <a href="/wiki/Hawick" title="Hawick">Hawick</a> and <a href="/wiki/Selkirk,_Scottish_Borders" title="Selkirk, Scottish Borders">Selkirk</a>. The Abbeys were homes to the monks who lived there between the 12th and 16th centuries. The area was also home to a much earlier Abbey of <a href="/w/index.php?title=Tironsian&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="Tironsian (page does not exist)">Tironsian Abbey</a>, though it was short lived.</p>
<p></p>
